<br>
Trying to answer some of your earlier question Arlos, but this thread has digressed into personal attacks on the president about his Tolerance.  But I will do the best I can.<br>
<br>
Religion dictates a lifestyle.  In such, it also dictates a morality.  Buddhists, Hindis, Shintoists, etc. all maintain some form of moral character judgements or implied behavior.  Buddhism for example with its Eightfold path, which describes the steps one takes to attain 'liberation'.  Each of these teaches some form of moral or social behavior.  All religions do such.  That is the basis of religion.<br>
<br>
My original point was that no matter what religion, the impact on social life is part of the actual point of the religion.  Religion was formed to help Man become a more social creature in the first place.  To help him find a peace with the chaotic world around him.<br>
<br>
As for the rest, I don't have time to answer but I will say something about the Shamans.  I am not going to get into the politics of why a Commanche Shaman can't use his Peyote, I am not one to say.  But I do understand that most American Indians get special liberties on their reservations that normal americans don't get.  Granted they have been fugged over royally and deserve those benefits, but I am not one to criticize the actions of our ancestors.  Are you sure that it is illegal to use the drug in rituals as long as they are doing it on their reservation.  Unfortunately, I do not have much information to make any real clear determination, not that any decision I made would matter.<br>
<br>
Sorry If I didn't get to all the rest.  Just not enough time.<br>
