<br>
What I cannot abide however, is someone of such a religion trying to dictate to *ME* how *I* (or to anyone not of their religion, really) should act, when I do *NOT* follow their religion. My religion (and buddhist, and shintoist, and hindu, etc.) teaches a different set of moral rules than yours. By constitutional definition, none of these sets of moral rules are in any way inferior or lesser than yours. So, if my moral road map is different BUT EQUAL to your road map, if you try and force yours on me, aren't you violating my constitutional rights to practice my religion my way?<br>
<br>
Christianity teaches Drugs are Bad. MANY others do not. Why are those others forced to follow the tenets of a different religion? Christianity teaches Homosexuality is Bad. MANY Others do not. So why is there society-wide prejudice against people who happen to be gay? Aren't their individual rights being trampled on to marry or OPENLY be in the military, if they follow a faith that says their lifestyle is perfectly OK?<br>
<br>
That's why even if someone is a devout christian in their private life, it is WRONG for them to attempt to make PUBLIC policy based on it. If each of our moral paths is equal by the constitution, if you are making legislation based on ONE religion, you are telling EVERY SINGLE OTHER religion that they do not enjoy the same standing under the law as christianity does. How is that constitutional?<br>
<br>
Do you see now? Do you see how forcing everyone, regardless of what religion they REALLY are to follow the Christian Moral Path IS oppression of those people, and breaks the constitution? Indeed, it even is oppression on CHRISTIAN sects that have different belief patterns than the particular sect that that particular lawmaker belongs to does.<br>
<br>
As for the shamanism thing, it is possible it has changed in the last 10-15 years. I do know that a friend of mine in high school was a native american, and moved back to his tribal reservation after he graduated, so he could undergo training and study to be a shaman for his tribe. He mentioned it as an issue at that time when we talked after he'd been back there a bit. I haven't talked to him in 8-9 years, and no clue where he is now, so I can't ask current status, but that's how it was then.<br>
<br>
