<br>
My point is: What gives *YOU* the right to tell *ME* that I'm wrong? The CONSTITUTION says that no one religion shall be placed above another. So why should *I*, who am not christian, be FORCED into following christian moral rules? Isn't that placing YOUR religion over me, which we just learned is supposedly UNCONSTITUTIONAL?<br>
<br>
BTW, re: cigarettes and weed, show me where I said it was OK to inflict one's personal choices on other people? Hasn't that been exactly what I've been arguing *AGAINST* in every single of one of my posts? If I am smoking tobacco or pot around other people then aren't I inflicting my choice upon them? However, if I am kicking back at home, in my PRIVATE space, then I effect no one but me. So where's the problem?<br>
<br>
If you chose to smoke cigarettes in a non-public space, I say that is absolutely your right. It is your body, and no one but you should be able to tell you what you can and cannot do to it of your own free will. That applies whether it's cigarettes, pot, alcahol, most other things. Some drugs, like PCP, which are known to cause psychosis, obviously should not be legal. Pot, for example on the other hand, has been shown to be impossible to OD on, causes lethargy, and has been shown to cause far less long-term health problems on moderate use than equivalent use of alcahol.<br>
<br>
Hey, yes, drugs DO impair judgement. Gosh, so does being drunk. Funny, drinking is legal, though it impairs judgement worse than some currently illegal drugs. How do you reconcile THAT? Please re-read where I said that they need to be something done in a private space, in a responsible manner, just like people need to be responsible drinkers. You drive under the influence of ANYTHING, you're not responsible and should be tossed in jail. I can't, however, see how someone who smokes weed and then spends the next 2 hours on the couch watching Spongebob Squarepants is a danger to ANYONE.<br>
<br>
